d of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda Fitzrobert was born in 1155, in England, her father, William FitzRobert 2nd Earl of Gloucester, was 39 and her mother, Hawise de Beaumont, was 41. She married Hamby before 1170, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1208, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1155–1208":"1155–1208","1148–1162":"1148–1162","1150–1166":"1150–1166","1150–1183":"1150–1183","1160–1225":"1160–1225","1173–1217":"1173–1217","1161–1212":"1161–1212","–Male":"Surnud","1184–Male":"1184–Surnud","1170–1225":"1170–1225","1116–1183":"1116–1183","1114–1197":"1114–1197","about 1170":"umbes 1170","24 April 1197":"24. aprill 1197","1197":"1197","1184":"1184","1173":"1173","1162":"1162","1150":"1150","1161":"1161","1183":"1183","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1217":"1217","1116":"1116","1225":"1225","1148":"1148","1114":"1114","1212":"1212","1155":"1155","1166":"1166","23 November 1183":"23. november 1183","before 1184":"enne 1184","before 1170":"enne 1170","12